[3] Japan
Date: 11 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: East Day [edited]
<http://english.eastday.com/epublish/gb/paper1/1204/class000100003/hwz185297.htm>

Dead chickens test negative for bird flu in Japan
--------------------------------------------------
More than 100 chickens were found dead Thursday in western Japan, but
following tests almost ruled out the possibility of fresh bird flu outbreak.
The case took place at a slaughterhouse in Kitakyushu, Fukuoka Prefecture,
where 126 among 930 chickens were found dead, Kyodo News quoted local
government as saying. But the tests on 10 dead chickens proved negative for
bird flu, the report said.
Further tests are expected to be conducted, and a veterinarian said the
chance of avian flu infection was "extremely low," Kyodo reported. Japan
has seen 3 bird flu outbreaks since January 2004. In the latest hit in late
February, around 250 000 chickens died either from virus or slaughter. The
67-year-old farm owner and his 64-year-old wife committed suicide Monday
amid accusations the husband was attempting to cover up the death of chickens.
Some chicken and eggs from that farm have reached restaurants in
neighboring areas. However, no human infection has been found in Japan's
first bird flu outbreaks over 79 years.
The Japanese authorities are now concerned about the disease being spread
by birds after some crows tested positive for the disease.
******
[4] Thailand
Date: 11 Mar 2004
From: Dunja Minet <minet@loxinfo.co.th>
Source: Bangkok Post [edited]
<http://www.bangkokpost.com/News/11Mar2004_news09.php>

Bird flu: Chiang Rai outbreak confirmed; Upsets plan to declare country
disease free
--------------------------------------------
Deputy Agriculture Minister Newin Chidchob's plan to declare Thailand free
of bird flu by early next week has collapsed after an outbreak in Chiang
Rai was confirmed.
The minister revealed the outbreak yesterday, 2 weeks after the bird flu
was detected in the province.
Mr Newin was forced into the confirmation after a Thai-language newspaper
published a test result on bird flu-infected chicken from Chiang Rai.
The lab result was dated 26 Feb 2004, a day after the government lifted all
red alert zones.
An affected poultry farmer said he repeatedly told the Livestock Department
about the outbreak, but was ignored.
Mr Newin claimed the department tested a chicken carcass from an infected
farm earlier, but the result was negative.
"Unconvinced, the poultry farmer sent the chicken carcass to Kasetsart
University's lab, which confirmed the fowl was infected with H5N1 virus
strain of bird flu on Feb 26," said Mr Newin. ''Livestock officials
immediately culled the chickens within a [specified] radius of the farm.
The operation ended on 2 Mar 2004, and the area is now under 21-day
surveillance."
If no there were no more cases the area would be downgraded to a green zone
on 23 Mar 2004, he said.
Mr Newin said officials were also testing suspicious chicken carcasses from
Chachoengsao's Phanom Sarakham district. Mr Newin said on Monday that with
no more reports of mass chicken deaths since the mass culling operation
ended on 25 Feb 2004, the country could be declared bird-flu free under
International Organisation for Animal Health rules on 16 Mar, if no new
case of bird flu emerged. The Chiang Rai outbreak means a change of plan,
with the ministry declaring bird flu-free zones area by area, rather than
for the whole country.
[Byline: Kultida Samabuddhi]
